–Female":"1305–Overleden","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","before 1300":"vóór 1300","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1305":"circa 1305","1305":"1305","1347":"1347","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1332":"1332","about 1330":"circa 1330","after 1332":"na 1332","about 1285":"circa 1285","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italië","Wales":"Wales","Of Yr Hendwr, Llandrillo-yn-ed, Merionethshire, Wales":"Llandrillo, Merionethshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Llandrillo-yn-Edeirnion, Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales"},"en":{"1270–after 1332":"1270–after 1332","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1270–1344":"1270–1344","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","before 1300":"before 1300","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1305":"about 1305","1305":"1305","1347":"1347","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1332":"1332","about 1330":"about 1330","after 1332":"after 1332","about 1285":"about 1285","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","Wales":"Wales","Of Yr Hendwr, Llandrillo-yn-ed, Merionethshire, Wales":"Llandrillo, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llandrillo-yn-Edeirnion, Merionethshire, Wales":"Merionethshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelhard</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelhard</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Yr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Hong, Jian, Qing, Feng, Zhong, Bin, Jin, Li, Mei, Min, Ming, Wen.  Korean Chol, Dong Sup, Jong Chul, Myong, Neng, Sook Young, Sung Chul.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 葉, meaning ‘leaf’ in Chinese: (i) from the placename Ye (葉), the name of a fief (located in Henan province) granted to Shen Zhu Liang, son of an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) traced back to a minority ethnic group in ancient southern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 野: shortened form of the Chinese surname Dong-Ye (東野), which was derived from name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to Yu, nephew of King Wu of Zhou (<i>c.</i> 1087–1043  BC )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yip","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wai, Wing, Ching, Lai, Chi, Chi Hung, Chun, Kam, Kan, Man, Shu, Yuk.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 葉, see   Ye   1."]},{"name":"Yep","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Jing, Shin, Tong, Wai, Wing Fong.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 葉, see   Ye   1."]},{"name":"Yap","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Enrique, Jose, Alberto, Carlos, Fernando, Rodolfo, Rolando, Rosalina, Vincente, Adela, Adoracion, Alfredo.","Chinese: Hakka and Hokkien Romanization of the surname 葉, see   Ye   1. The dialects using this form are found in Guangdong, Fujian and Taiwan, from where many people migrated to Singapore, Malaysia, the Philippines, and Thailand, and other parts of Southeast Asia.","Americanized form of North German   Japp  ."]},{"name":"Yu","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Ming, Yong, Young, Ping, Chi, Chun, Jae, Li, Sung, Jin, Yang.  Korean Chung, Chang, Byung, Chong, Min, Pyong, Myong, Hyong, Moon, Yiu, Inyoung, Shiu.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 余 (or rarely written as 餘), meaning ‘I’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the second element of the personal name You Yu (由余), the name of a prime minister in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from Yu (余), the name of a small state during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) said to be borne by descendants of Xia Yu, the first king of the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 于 (meaning ‘go’ in ancient Chinese) or 於 (often simplified as 于 in Mainland China, meaning ‘depend on’ in ancient Chinese): (i) simplified form of the Chinese character 邘, the name of an ancient state (located in Qinyang in Henan province), which was granted to Yu Shu (邘叔), the third son of King Wen of Zhou (1152–1056  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Zheng during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), the Chinese character 邘 (pronounced Yu) was simplified to (于) and adopted as a surname. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Wan Niu Yu (萬忸于) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) adopted in place of the Chinese compound surname Chun-Yu (淳于), because the first element of the surname, Chun, happened to share the same pronunciation with the personal name of the emperor Li Chun, also known as Emperor Xianzong of Tang (778–820  AD ), which was taboo in ancient China. (iv) said to be traced back to Yu Ze (於則), who said to be the inventor of shoes, an official the legendary Huang Di, the ‘Yellow Emperor’ (<i>c.</i> 27th century  BC ). (v) from the second element of the placename Shang Yu (商於) in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Yeh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Ching, Ming, Cheng, Chin, Hui, Hui Chun, Ping, Yuan, Chi, Chien, Ching Ling, Ching Yu.","Chinese:","alternative Mandarin form of the surname 葉, see   Ye   1."]}]},{"name":"Hendwr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish: habitational name from any of several places in Cornwall named <i>Hendra</i>, from Cornish <i>hen dref</i> ‘old homestead’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hendra","meanings":["Cornish (Cornwall and Devon): variant of   Hender  ."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Madog ap Iowerth Argylwydd ap Yr Hendwr was born in 1270, in Merionethshire, Wales as the son of Iowerth Argylwydd Ap Yr Hendower. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Efa ferch Llywelyn. He died after 1332, in Wales."},"et":{"1270–after 1332":"1270–pärast 1332","1270–1332":"1270–1332","1270–1344":"1270–1344","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","before 1300":"enne 1300","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Abt 1305":"umbes 1305","1305":"1305","1347":"1347","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1344":"1344","1332":"1332","about 1330":"umbes 1330","after 1332":"pärast 1332","about 1285":"umbes 1285","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","Wales":"Wales","Of Yr Hendwr, Llandrillo-yn-ed, Merioneths